english:
  title: A Letter to the Mountain Recluse Owsaeng
  author: Lim Chun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I bow respectfully to the east and send this humble letter across distant hills to the Mountain Recluse of Gaya and his attendant Saenggong.

    Long have I observed how the worthy sages of old regarded the world—neither stubbornly differing from it nor slavishly conforming to it. When summoned to serve, they became teachers of emperors; when cast aside, they became but solitary hermits in remote valleys. Thus their actions and stillness, their words and silences, all found their proper place.

    When chaos recently swept the land, men rushed to hide themselves in shadows and donned false vestments to escape the moment's peril. Yet when the tide of fortune turned, before even a royal summons could arrive, they eagerly grasped for wealth and position, scrambling without shame. Who among them still held fast to that noble seclusion?

    Thus have the hidden worthies grown scarce in our age, though they were once as common as stars. The steadfast resolve of Chi and Yin—unwavering from beginning to end—their spirits pure and bright as autumn frost, sharp enough to stir even the corrupt to shame: such virtue dwells only in you and in the Recluse of Pukwon, Master Kwon.

    I have long wished to cast off my robes and journey to you, to wander in your company, yet I have never managed to brush aside the clouds and knock upon your mountain gate. Day and night I have only sighed with longing. Now I understand how difficult it is for one dwelling in the marketplace to truly admire the lofty heights of mountain hermitage. Alas! To know return only after falling into hardship—this cannot be called seeing opportunity and seizing it. Yet should I purchase a small plot and become a humble farmer, growing old and dying there without sorrow, would that not suffice?

    Once I wandered in the land of Danzhou, where the mountains and waters were surpassingly fair—a place worthy of settling one's hermitage. There the stone cliffs rose in wondrous beauty, and to the east lay an abandoned site. Upon inquiry, I learned it belonged to a commoner whose lands were burdened with official taxes and private debts, their sale repeatedly attempted but never successful. Hearing this gladdened my heart, yet I lacked the means to purchase it or the wealth to develop it.

    But now the learned Master Yi, a man of true understanding, has become my kindred spirit. I sought to borrow his resources to gather materials in those mountain valleys, and having made my request, I received his consent. Before the first month of summer ends, I shall raise a humble cottage and lead my family there. I shall also purchase several fields along the river to sustain us through the seasons. Such is my plan.

    Last autumn I sent a servant bearing letters across a thousand li to seek aid from the Bodhisattva Temple and the Reverend Seon. His reply came with promises of assistance—a cause for both shame and joy. The ancients knew well those who loved to aid others' urgency, who held wealth as lightly as dust. The wandering heroes of the Qin and Han embodied this spirit, yet such virtue is rarely seen in our time. Yet for one of the Reverend's wisdom and reach, is this not a trifle?

    With this understanding, I made my request without hesitation. Should I ever have the fortune to attend upon you, perhaps you might speak gently of this matter to the Reverend, so that my humble plan might reach completion—that would be a great blessing indeed. I now also send a letter to Master Yi, hoping he will convey it to the Reverend, so that he may know my request springs not from mere chance, but from sincere intention. Even should he offer no material aid, I shall feel as though I have received his gifts.

    I have long heard that you excel in cursive script. Whenever a visitor from the south arrives, I have sought specimens, yet never have I obtained them—a source of constant regret. All calligraphy mirrors the character of its writer. When one beholds the bold strokes of Yan Lugong, one seems to witness him rebuking Lu Chi and striking at Xilie himself. From your spirited and transcendent nature, I can well imagine your script must echo such majesty.

    Yet my heart still yearns to see the true work from your hand. In the mountain's quiet days, surely you have much leisure. If you would not begrudge us such a gift—to see your brush sweep across the page—what fortune that would be! My words fall short. I bow again respectfully.
  footnotes:
    - The letter addresses a Buddhist monk called 'Saenggong' (生公) who resides at Gaya Mountain, asking him to assist Lim Chun in fulfilling his dream of retirement and simple farming.
    - References to Chi and Yin allude to the legendary hermits who embodied perfect withdrawal from public service—ideals central to East Asian literati philosophy.
    - Yan Lugong (顔魯公) was a Tang Dynasty calligrapher famous for both his artistic excellence and unwavering moral integrity; the reference to his striking Lu Chi and Xilie evokes his political resistance.
    - The letter skillfully interweaves personal aspiration, philosophical reflection on reclusion, practical requests for assistance, and aesthetic appreciation of the addressee's talents.
